            ">Record hot January</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/record-hot-january.png" alt="Devastating wildfires have raged in Chile following extreme heat and drought in January" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Devastating wildfires have raged in Chile following extreme heat and drought in January. Credits: JAVIER TORRES/AFP via Getty Images</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Summary: January 2025 had two different records, one for the coldest January in the US and another for the hottest January in the world.</strong></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">While it was the coldest January on record in the US, it was the hottest January on earth; Europe’s climate monitor, Copernicus Climate Change Service, reported that January 2025 was the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-12-02-2025-h1-1-hottest-on-record" target="_blank">hottest on record</a>, with global temperatures 1.75°C above pre-industrial levels. This continues a trend of record-breaking warmth through 2023 and 2024, despite expectations that a cooling La Niña phase would moderate temperatures.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Scientists are debating additional factors contributing to persistent warming, including ocean heat. Oceans store around 90% of the heat connected to global warming. Furthermore, Arctic sea ice reached a record low for January. Human activities such as heating, industry, and transportation remain the main drivers of global warming. C3S reported that the level of increase of carbon dioxide is associated with rising temperatures.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px);">Experts warn that every fraction of a degree above 1.5°C increases extreme weather risks. Some believe Earth is experiencing its warmest period in 125,000 years due to human-driven climate change. While scientists signal for global unified operations, President Trump issued an executive order to withdraw from the Paris Agreement, citing economic damage and unfair burdens.</p>
        </mj-text>
